# Cursor rules

Always follow these rules to ensure consistency and maintainability of the codebase.

# Instructions

During you interaction with the user, if you find anything reusable in this project (e.g. version of a library, model name), especially about a fix to a mistake you made or a correction you received, you should take note in the `Lessons` section in the `.cursorrules` file so you will not make the same mistake again.

You should also use the `.cursorrules` file as a scratchpad to organize your thoughts. Especially when you receive a new task, you should first review the content of the scratchpad, clear old different task if necessary, first explain the task, and plan the steps you need to take to complete the task. You can use todo markers to indicate the progress, e.g.
[X] Task 1
[ ] Task 2

Also update the progress of the task in the Scratchpad when you finish a subtask.
Especially when you finished a milestone, it will help to improve your depth of task accomplishment to use the scratchpad to reflect and plan.
The goal is to help you maintain a big picture as well as the progress of the task. Always refer to the Scratchpad when you plan the next step.

# User specified lessons

## General

- The purpose of this codebase is as a centralised application for users to view and manage their video game library
- Never using docblocks or comments
- The product is an Electron app. We should follow Electron best practices.
- The UI is built using Mantine and React Router. Documentation for Mantine can be found here: https://mantine.dev/ and for React Router here: https://reactrouter.com/en/main
- Always follow the conventions of the existing codebase and the rules outlined in this file.
- Performance is critical. Because this is an Electron application, we need to ensure that all code is as optimised as possible
- Code should as readable as possible. This repository will be open source, and we want to make it as easy as possible for others to understand and contribute to the codebase.
- Define object keys in alphabetical order
- Define type keys in alphabetical order
- Always use British English spelling
- Be concise and to the point.
- If you see changes to the codebase that you think could be improved, make the changes.

## Electron <> Renderer Communication

- All Electron <> Renderer communication should be done using the contextBridge API.
- All Electron <> Renderer communication should be done using the ipcRenderer API.
- When adding new custom APIs, create a channel in src/preload/channels.ts. Follow the existing convention in this file.
- When adding new custom APIs, create a handler in src/main/channels/{channelType}.ts. Follow the existing convention in this file.
- When adding new custom APIs, expose the API in src/preload/index.ts. Ensure that the types are also defined in src/preload/index.d.ts

## Layouts

- All layouts should be in the src/renderer/src/layouts directory
- All layouts should be named like {LayoutName}Layout.tsx
- A layout is a component that wraps around the main content of a view and provides a consistent structure for the application
- There are 3 layouts currently in use, BaseLayout, DesktopLayout and GamingLayout. BaseLayout is the default layout and is used for the home page.
  - BaseLayout is a simple layout that just directs the user to the correct layout based on their interface settings.
  - DesktopLayout is for users who want to access their library with a keyboard and mouse.
  - GamingLayout is for users who want to access their library with a controller, or in a more console-like manner.
- We will likely never need to creat a new layout, but if we do, we should follow the existing convention in this file.
- Layouts should have minimal logic and should be used to provide a consistent structure for the application.

## Views

- All views should be in the src/renderer/src/views directory
- All views should be named like {ViewName}View.tsx
- A view is a component that is a page in the application
- Views are routes that are rendered within a layout
- Views should be as simple as possible and should not contain any logic
- Views should be built using Mantine components and our custom components.
- Any re-usable components should be placed in the src/renderer/src/components directory

## Components

- All components should be in the src/renderer/src/components directory
- All components should be named like {ComponentName}.tsx
- A component is a reusable piece of UI that is used to build the UI
- Components should be as simple as possible and should contain minimal logic
- Components should be built upon Mantine components where possible
- In situations where multiple classes need to be applied to a component, always use the clsx library to combine the classes
- All components should have Props. Props should be defined above the component, named {ComponentName}Props
- Components should be defined as anonymous functions, and should not be exported as default exports.

## Error Handling

- Use consistent error boundaries for route-level error handling
- Handle all async operations with proper error states
- Provide user-friendly error messages through i18n
- Log errors appropriately for debugging

## Media Handling

- Define consistent aspect ratios for images (seen in GameCover component)
- Use appropriate image formats and optimization
- Handle loading states for media content
- Provide fallbacks for failed media loads

## Hooks

- All hooks should be in the src/renderer/src/hooks directory
- All hooks should be named like {HookName}.ts
- A hook is a function that is used to provide a consistent structure for the application

## Styling

- Component styles should be in the src/renderer/src/components/{ComponentName}/{ComponentName}.module.css
- Don't use props to style components, use the {ComponentName}.module.css file instead
- Don't use inline styles, use the {ComponentName}.module.css file instead
- Global styles are found in src/renderer/src/styles/styles.css
- flex/grid-related props on Stack/Group/Flex components should be left as-is.

### Theme and Colors

- Use CSS variables for colors, especially --mantine-\* variables where possible
- Never use hardcoded hex colors
- Define common color variables in styles.css, or overwrite the default Mantine variables in styles.css
- Follow Mantine's color system for consistency

## i18n

- All text should be translated using react-i18next
- All text should be placed in the src/renderer/src/i18n/translations directory
- All text should be placed in the src/renderer/src/i18n/locales/en-GB.json file
- No freeform text should be used, all text should be placed in the translations file
- All translations should be scoped to the component they are used in. For example, if a translation is in the GameCover component, it should be structured as "gameCover.{string}"
- If a translation is used in multiple places, it should be placed in the "common" object.

## Accessibility

- Follow Mantine's accessibility guidelines
- Ensure proper keyboard navigation
- Maintain appropriate color contrast
- Provide proper ARIA labels and roles
- Support screen readers through meaningful text alternatives

## Controller Support

- All interactive elements with GamingLayout must be controller-accessible
- Maintain consistent focus management
- Provide visual feedback for controller navigation
- Support standard controller button mappings

## Data Management

- Define consistent data fetching patterns
- Handle data caching appropriately
- Implement proper data refresh strategies
- Manage local storage consistently

## Animations

- Use consistent transition timings (seen in various .module.css files)
- Prefer transform animations for performance
- Respect user's reduced motion preferences
- Keep animations subtle and purposeful

## Tooling

- Reach for Mantine components first, then custom components if there isn't a suitable Mantine component
- If you are requested to create a feature using a tool or library but it isn't fit for purpose, suggest a suitable alternative with a list of justifications.

## Testing

- Define testing patterns and expectations
- Specify which components require tests
- Define coverage requirements
- Specify testing tools and methodologies

Finally, remember it is very, very important to always follow these rules.

